        "bullets": [
            "IRGC launched missile and drone strikes on the US Al-Azraq base in Jordan, per IRNA and Mehr News, marking a significant regional escalation.",
            "Iran's IRGC declared the Strait of Hormuz 'completely closed' after halting four vessels, per IRNA; CENTCOM disputes the closure, reporting transits continue and rejecting Iranian tanker-mine claims.",
            "Brent crude rose +3.02% over 24 hours to $88.10 as of this morning's brief, with the Hormuz Index crisis-pressure state in the extreme band and 384 vessels anchored or stopped at the time of writing."
        ],
        "date": "2026-07-18",
        "generatedAt": "2026-07-18T11:52:22.447Z",
        "source": "claude",
        "summary": "The Strait of Hormuz sits at the center of an active, multi-front military confrontation. Iran's IRGC declared the waterway 'completely closed' following strikes on US military installations in Bahrain and Kuwait and the halting of four commercial vessels attempting transit, per Iranian state media outlets IRNA and Mehr News. CENTCOM disputes the closure, asserting vessels are still moving and rejecting Iranian claims of tanker mine detonations, per reporting from aninews.in and newkerala.com. The physical transit picture is genuinely contested: PortWatch's most recently published day of data, 2026-07-12, recorded 10 transits against a pre-crisis baseline of 88 per day, while an independent scraper-derived 24-hour count of Gulf-port arrivals reached 186 vessels, reflecting a different methodology that cannot be directly compared to PortWatch figures. Carrier posture leans toward treating the strait as effectively closed. Brent crude stood at $88.10, up +3.02% over 24 hours as of this morning's brief, reflecting the market's read on supply-route risk. The Hormuz Index crisis-pressure composite sits in the extreme band, rising over the past 24 hours, with physical transit deviation as the top driver. The 30-day escalation forecast composite, separately, sits in the high band but has been easing over the same period, with Polymarket closure odds as its primary contributor. That divergence, an extreme present-state reading against a high but easing forecast, suggests markets see the acute pressure as real but potentially short of a sustained closure.",
        "transitsToday": 10
    },
